questions.text: In a star, gravity is trying to:
choices: Expand the star outward (make it bigger)
Pull the star into itself (make it smaller)
Move the star closer to other stars
Turn it into a black hole
questions.solution: Turn it into a black hole
questions.solutionText: Gravity is always pulling toward the center of an object, trying to collapse a star in on itself, making the star smaller. In high mass stars, this could result in the formation of a black hole, but most stars don't have enough mass for this to happen. Even in these smaller stars, gravity is still pulling the star in on itself.

questions.text: In a star, energy is trying to
choices: Turn it into a black hole
Pull the star into itself (make it smaller)
Expand the star outward (make it bigger)
Move the star closer to other stars
questions.solution: Expand the star outward (make it bigger)
questions.solutionText: The energy from the fusion of elements in the core of a star is constantly pushing a star outward, expanding and getting bigger. Things with higher energy generally move faster and collide with the materials around them, causing them to be pushed outward. When this is happening all throughout the star, the effect is a "pushing" outward from the center of the star.

questions.text: What causes spaghettification?
questions.solutionText: Spaghettification is what happens to something that gets pulled into a black hole. The tidal forces from the difference in gravity on one end of an object compared to the gravity on the opposite end of the object are enough to stretch out the object falling into the black hole like a piece of spaghetti.

questions.text: After the Sun has used up all its hydrogen, which phase of its life will it enter?
questions.solutionText: When the Sun can no longer fuse hydrogen, it must begin fusing helium. This process gives off more energy than hydrogen fusion, causing the Sun to expand and its outer layers to cool (becoming redder).

A star can keep making energy until its only fuel source is:
questions.solutionText: Big enough stars can fuse elements up to iron on the Periodic Table. Iron fusion is unique in that it absorbs more energy than it gives off. This means that if a star tries to fuse iron, it will actually take energy away from the star, preventing fusion from continuing.

questions.text: What is the Event Horizon of a black hole?
choices: The force that pulls objects into a black hole
The part where trapped light gathers
The part that used to be a star
The boundary beyond which light cannot escape
questions.solution: The boundary beyond which light cannot escape
questions.solutionText: A characteristic of black holes is gravity that is so strong, light itself cannot escape. The distance from the center of a black hole that marks the point beyond which light cannot escape gravity's pull is called the event horizon because an outside observer cannot see any events that happen beyond that point.

questions.text: Melvin wants to find out what it's like inside a black hole. He has an unlimited amount of money, and advanced technology available. What should he try?
choices: Tie a camera onto a super strong cable and drop it in from a spaceship and pull it out quickly
Forget it and go back to watching Star Wars.
Drop a wireless camera into the black hole from an orbiting spaceship
questions.solution: Forget it and go back to watching Star Wars.
questions.solutionText: There is no way to get any information out of a black hole. Light is the fastest thing in the universe and it is unable to escape the event horizon of a black hole. Any way we might try to transmit information out of a black hole uses light (radio waves are a form of light), so there is no way of transmitting information out of the black hole.

questions.text: In a star, there is an ongoing battle between:
questions.solutionText: Gravity is constantly trying to collapse the star in on its core, while the energy from fusion is pushing outward from the core. If the energy wasn't balanced by the gravity, the star would explode and if the gravity wasn't balanced by the energy, the star would collapse in on itself. When gravity and energy are balanced, the star's size is stable.

questions.text: An average star spends most of its life in this phase:
questions.solutionText: The Main Sequence is named because it is the main portion of a star's life. While there are other stages, the majority of the time a star exists, it's a main sequence star. Our Sun is currently on the main sequence.

questions.text: Which of these is a valid stellar lifetime sequence?
choices: Nebula, protostar, main sequence, red giant, supernova, neutron star
Nebula, protostar, main sequence, red giant, black hole
Nebula, protostar, main sequence, white dwarf, neutron star
Protostar, main sequence, red giant, supernova, black hole
questions.solution: Nebula, protostar, main sequence, red giant, black hole
questions.solutionText: All stars begin their lives as nebulas (huge clouds of gas and dust in space). Gravity pulls the gas & dust together forming a ball called a protostar. Once the pressure from the growing protostar's mass is high enough it will begin fusing hydrogen into helium and become a main sequence star, giving off visible light, like our Sun. Once the hydrogen fuel is used it, the star will expand to a red giant and start fusing helium. If the star is massive enough it will fuse until it can't fuse any more elements, explode into a supernova, leaving behind a black hole.

questions.text:
Rates & Ratios

It takes 4 cooks 4 hours to bake 4 cakes. Assuming no change of rate, how many hours will it take 8 cooks to bake 8 cakes?
questions.category_name: Algebra Through Puzzles: A Preview of Challenges to Come
questions.solutionText:
When considering a problem like this, we are interested in measuring the amount of man-hours (or cook-hours) that it takes to produce a cake. Four cooks all working for four hours will produce 16 cook-hours of work. Therefore, the relationship between cakes and work is \[\dfrac{16\text{ cook-hours}}{4\text{ cakes}} = \dfrac{4\text{ cook-hours}}{\text{ cake}}.\] Once we understand the relationship between work and cakes, we can use the equation \[\dfrac{(h)(C)}{c}=4,\] where \(h\) is the number of hours, \(C\) is the number of cooks, and \(c\) is the number of cakes.

Plugging in gives us \[\dfrac{(h)(8)}{8}=4\implies h=4.\]

questions.text:
Sequences and Series

How many line-segments are there in the \(4^\text{th}\) image of this growing tree sequence?
questions.category_name: Algebra Through Puzzles: A Preview of Challenges to Come
questions.solutionText:
SOLUTION 1:

In the first image in the sequence, there's only one line segment. In the next image, this branch splits adding 2 line segments to the picture. Then each of those splits adding 4 more. A final split adds 8 more small branches: \(1 + 2 + 4 + 8 = \fbox{15}.\)

SOLUTION 2:

In the previous tree, there are 7 branches. This tree is made up of two copies of that previous tree branching off of a new trunk: \((7 \times 2) + 1 = \fbox{15}.\)

So each tree has twice as many branches as the last tree, plus 1 new trunk, resulting in the sequence \[1, 3, 7, 15, \ldots.\]

questions.text:
Proving Algebraic Identities

What is the sum of the first 13 positive odd numbers?

A big hint:
questions.category_name: Algebra Through Puzzles: A Preview of Challenges to Come
questions.solutionText:
The sum of the first \(n\) odd numbers is \(n^2\)
A visualization of this claim:

Therefore, the sum of the first 13 odd numbers is \(13^2=169.\)

A Quick Proof:

Consider that the positive even numbers are those of the form \(2n\), where \(n\) can be any positive integer, starting with \(n=1\). Similarly, the odd numbers are, in turn, numbers of the form \(2n-1\), again where \(n\) can be any positive integer, starting with \(n=1\).

Here is a quick inductive proof that the sum of the first \(n\) odd numbers is \(n^2\):

Observe that \((n-1)^2 + (2n-1) = n^2 \). Since \(2n-1\) is the \(n^\text{th}\) odd number, if the statement is true for \(n\), it's now proven to also be true for \(n+1\). Clearly, the statement holds true for \(n=1\), so that can be our base case. And inductive reasoning takes over from there!

Let \( a = b \).

questions.category_name: Algebra Through Puzzles: A Preview of Challenges to Come
questions.solutionText:
Line 4 was achieved by involves dividing both sides of the equal sign by \( a-b \). However, since \( a = b ,\) \( a - b = 0 ,\) so this step involves dividing by zero.

By allowing the act of dividing by zero, the nonsensical statement \(1 = 2\) was a result.

questions.text:
The problems in this category should be done mentally. There are tricks that help with each one. Be creative!

Evaluate: 762 + 349= ?
questions.category_name: Algebra Through Puzzles: Arithmetic Tricks I
questions.solutionText:
Possible Trick #1:

Separate the sum into parts that are easier to add: 762 + 349 = 700 + 300 + 60 + 40 + 2 + 9 = 1000 + 100 + 11 = 1111

Possible Trick #2:

Take 1 away from 762 and add it to 349, creating more convenient numbers: 762 + 349 = 762 - 1 + 349 + 1 = 761 + 350 = 1111
